    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Pain after major arthroscopic surgery is dependent on an optimal multimodal analgesic
      treatment.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      Lidocaine is well-known as analgesic treatment on skin and hypodermic veins. Since 1996 it
      has been documented that topical lidocaine has an analgesic effect 24 hours after surgical
      treatment.

      The aim is to determine a possible reduction in pain after knee arthroscopy with topical
      lidocaine.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
